      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "The Innocence Project's financial health is characterized by a <cite id=\"14\">program expense ratio of 74.6%</cite>, which is supported by a lean administrative structure. Their governance is bolstered by an <cite id=\"15\">independent board of 17 members</cite>, ensuring objective oversight of their <cite id=\"16\">$105,843,645 in total assets</cite>. This financial strength allows them to manage complex, multi-year litigation and <cite id=\"17\">intake reviews for thousands of letters</cite> annually from incarcerated individuals seeking assistance."
      ],
      "summary": "The Innocence Project is a national nonprofit organization dedicated to <cite id=\"1\">freeing innocent people who have been wrongly convicted</cite> and reforming the criminal justice system. Founded in <cite id=\"2\">1992</cite>, the organization utilizes DNA testing and <cite id=\"3\">post-conviction litigation</cite> to overturn unjust incarcerations. In the 2023 fiscal year, the organization reported <cite id=\"4\">total revenue of $32,455,846</cite>, primarily driven by <cite id=\"5\">$26,644,804 in contributions</cite>. The organization maintains a <cite id=\"6\">program expense ratio of 74.6%</cite>, ensuring that the majority of funds are directed toward its core mission of legal advocacy and <cite id=\"7\">policy reform</cite>. Beyond individual exonerations, the Innocence Project works on <cite id=\"8\">strategic litigation and data science</cite> to identify and mitigate the causes of wrongful convictions, such as misidentification and false confessions. Their work has led to <cite id=\"9\">over 220 total exonerations</cite> documented through their historical filings, reflecting a long-term commitment to systemic justice. The organization is recognized for its <cite id=\"10\">perfect 100.0/100 from Charity Navigator</cite>, highlighting its commitment to transparency and financial accountability.",
